at phenomena of this kind have been underappreciated and have serious consequences for formal linguistic architecture. We accomplish this through breadth and depth studies. In order to better understand its extent and variation, we cull the linguistic literature for additional instances of multifunctional use of possessive marking across languages, building a publicly-accessible wiki to display them and access them for our own purposes (and for use by anyone interested in the public, academic or otherwise). In order to understand the multifunctionality in greater depth, we undertake detailed fieldwork on it in Ulwa, developing an analysis of possession in the context of Ulwa grammar that has the multifunctional use of the possessive marker as one of its explananda. We then explore the consequences of this analysis, both internal to Ulwa, and crosslinguistically. Internal to Ulwa, we carry out additional fieldwork on constructions in the language that are related to adjectives, specifically comparative constructions (e.g., Kim is taller than Sandy) and degree-based constructions (e.g., Kim is 6 feet tall), since our analysis of possession with adjectives involves a treatment of them in Ulwa whereby they have a fundamentally different meaning from their English counterparts, thereby raising questions about the analysis of constructions involving them. Beyond Ulwa, we undertake detailed fieldwork on Huave and Hausa to better understand the nature of the multifunctional use of possession in these languages and the extent to which it can or cannot be analyzed similarly to Ulwa.\n\nThe project will demonstrate, though this detailed case study, the consequences of taking multifunctionality seriously in formal linguistic analysis. Beyond this, it also has implications for the understanding of the nature of possession and crosslinguistic variation in the nature of the use of possessive marking. It will further contribute valuable data and analysis to developing efforts to understand the nature of variation in adjectival semantics crosslinguistically. Additionally, the data collected on Huave and Ulwa, both highly endangered languages, will contribute to the documentation of these languages at the same time that they shed light on the nature of language more broadly.\n\nResults of the project will be disseminated in the form of 6 conference presentations and 3 journal papers, outlined in the case for support</gtr:abstractText><gtr:potentialImpactText>The Huave and Ulwa communities, both of whose speakers have well-documented and ongoing concerns about the impending loss of their languages (Ulwa having approximately 350 speakers, all adults over the age of 40; and the Huave variety under investigation having fewer than 100, all elderly), will, in the long-term, extract benefits from this research, as the data collected as part of this project will contribute to documentation projects independently being carried out by Koontz-Garboden (Ulwa) and Kim (Huave). This documentation serves both cultural purposes for the speakers as well as more immediate educational purposes in the case of Ulwa, as speakers work toward the development of teaching materials for their language. Both Koontz-Garboden and Kim, although early-career scholars, have a history of carrying out not only work of a theoretical nature on these languages, but descriptive work as well (see, e.g., Kim's 2008 PhD and Koontz-Garboden's 2009 paper in International Journal of American Linguistics). Ulwa and Huave grammars are planned in the medium term for which the data gathered as part of this project will certainly be used.\n\n\n\n</gtr:potentialImpactText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2014-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9"><gtr:id>1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9</gtr:id><gtr:name>AHRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>165986</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The fieldwork on Huave (isolate; Oaxaca, Mexico) supported by this grant has supported a variety of Community-Based Endangered Language Revitalization Support activities, including
(i) Workshops on language pedagogy and Huave grammar for primary school teachers, Escuela primaria biling&amp;uuml;e 12 de Octubre, San Francisco del Mar, Oaxaca, Mexico, (ii) contribution to community orthography meetings, and (iii) Informal mentoring of parents and children who are learning Huave in order to revitalise it as a language used at home.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2012</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>42397B67-F597-44F6-A072-48D975DC9824</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56cb22f32c3eb6.67772627</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The major high-level finding of this research project is that variation in the structure of sentences expressing the same meanings is at least partly a consequence of variation in the inventory of word meanings. The project showed in relation to sentences in familiar languages where the main predicate is an adjective, e.g., Kim is beautiful, that in languages where there is a noun, e.g., beauty, rather than the corresponding adjective, that often times this noun has a meaning quite different to that of the adjective, and one which forces a different morphosyntax for the expression of the same meaning of the sentence with the adjectival counterpart.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The project explored cases where adjectival notions are expressed nominally. Many languages use verbs for their expression instead. The consequences of this point of variation are still poorly understood and in need of further exploration. 

The consequences of the observations also remain to be explored for the semantics of adjectives in familiar languages. The orthodox view in the semantics literature is that adjectives have a semantics based on the notion of degree. Whether degrees are the right kind of ontological object to be assumed to be in the denotation of nominal adjectival notions or not is an outstanding question. Further, it is as yet unclear whether the denotations of adjectives have the denotation of possessive morphosyntax + nominal adjectival notion. E.g., does 'have beauty' have the same meaning as 'beautiful'? Answering this question will shed further light on the scope of semantic variation.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>042CAA2F-4A80-4388-8157-C56D371D8642</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56cb22b8a536f7.18988448</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Creative Economy,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software)</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2516CF0C-1CEC-417F-A179-7FF29A6D583E</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Oxford Handbook of Derivational Morphology</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/592f23ded4595bda9ec40fb31399378b"><gtr:id>592f23ded4595bda9ec40fb31399378b</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Lieber R</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780199641642</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>56cb2072887d19.73634506</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>213A4781-992A-4049-B9E1-1EAEABA23E76</gtr:id><gtr:title>The universality of lexical categories: Comments on Chung</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Theoretical Linguistics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/e3c1542b9